So I added a strip of "gripper" tape from Lowes to the lower portion of the inner diameter and a couple pieces of electrical tape to keep the edges of it from peeling up. description.text:
Bob Huston did a great remix of my neck by adding two side pistons which give some more degree of freedom to the InMoov head.

Since I travel a lot with InMoov, I constantly need to dismantle the head to pack the robot in the suitcases. For that reason I redesigned some parts to make it easy to remove the head with only 4 screws.

I also added a ring to be glued, this avoids the ball joint to pop out. (Shown on pictures with my index finger)

ArtNeck_NeckJointUpperV4 is also modified to fit InMoov head, and doesn't need to be sanded down on the edges. Bob's model was a bit too large and would hit the inside of the head.

The connection between the two servos is done the same than with the InMoov Stomach.
One servo master controls a servo slave.
See Stomach tutorial:

A set of magnetic nesting measuring spoons.  Stick them to your fridge and never have to search for your measuring spoons again!

I designed these with the intent of mixing/matching colors.  The two sets pictured were the very first test runs.  
The white set was printed at standard resolution (in:10%, 2 shells, lh:0.20).  Print time was about 2 hours and the result was a little rought.  
The red set was printed at high resolution (in:15%, 3 shells, lh:0.10).  Print time was 5 1/2 hours, but the result was much cleaner (and more presentable in the kitchen).

description.text:
This adapter is based on the brilliant idea of CallJoe: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2524206, using a Low Cost Automotive Caliper Buck.
I used his idea to make an adapter to clamp the caliper on the fan-case of the Creality CR10. You can check with it and linearize the 4 corner-points of the heating-bed and compare/adjust the measured "zero" to the (most used) level in the middle of the bed. If the middle doesn't match, tape the "holes" with painters masking tape (mostly 0,1mm), so that all 5 levels become approximately equal.
Tip for leveling the bed: Disable the "G28" homing-commad in the generated gcode with a semicolon ;G28 and replace this with manually "Autohoming" on the printer before beginning, then disable the stepper-drivers to manually correct the levels with the 4 leveling-nuts on the 4 corners of the print-bed, then put the bed back to the home-position and go with the print – but dont forget to remove the Caliper+Adapter, because it suffuses the front-cooling-fan of the extruder!...
Upgrade: Version-2 has an air-gap between the holder and the case, letting a gap for the air sucked into the cooling-fan. Att.: It is essencial to slice this thing with PLA-Support!
So: have fun with the CR10!

Otherwise, if you have any questions about how to assemble please check out the "Exploded View" or feel free to shoot me a message. There are cutouts to pop each block and piece into the back of the cover so if you're sticking something in the wrong place you will know it. Also, PLEASE pay attention to where you put the lock bolts when you're setting their teeth in with the other gears. They MUST be butting up against the far edge so that they're sticking out as far as they can go when you assemble otherwise it will not work right.

**EDIT: I added in a blank sword emblem top and a blank cover page so that you may add whatever design/theme you want to your heart's desire :)

The grapevine motif was printed using ABS filament on acrylic sheet. As we discovered a while back, the ABS/acrylic combo has great stick properties and is almost impossible to release, which is perfect for this application. After the print finished I laid a sheet of annealed copper over it and embossed it under a 40 ton hydraulic press using a urethane conforming die. You can see signs made using this technique at http://www.copperimpressons.com This thing was featured on the 3D Printing Today podcast available on iTunes, Stitcher radio or direct from the source at http://threedprintingtoday.libsyn.com/

comments.text: It is quite possible to do it without the press, it just takes longer and the result isn't quite as regular.  Lay your annealed copper on the printed die.  I would probably clamp it in the corners to keep it in place.  Smack the copper with a rubber mallet.  You will see the pattern starting to transfer through the copper.  Once you have got the general layout of the pattern set in the copper you can go in with traditional chasing tools and shape it more precisely to the pattern.  This requires a lot of time and a fair amount of skill, but the results can be spectacular.  I use the hydraulic press because I am doing it as quickly and cheaply as possible because I am selling it to a client.

The Bike Hook design by ljblk is great but I needed something more flexible. I store the family bikes in the cellar of our small house and there isn´t much room for 6 bikes. Especially if you want to ride the bike all the way back and have to remove 5 bikes first before you can get what you realy want.

So, my idea was to combine ljblks hook with a carriage to push the bikes together while storing and beeing able to seperate to choose one if needed. All attached to a rail, mounted to the ceillig and at costs not more than a few bucks.

Here is the solution. All printed in PLA, Hook with hole for a M5 nut, fixed with an M5x50 screw to the "trolley housing". The wheel axle is a M6x60 with 2 washers and a stop nut.

I bought 2m of 3/4" pipe for cold water which is made of steel, 2 clamps for it and 2 S10 dowel (which can hold apx 75kg each).

After the hook. wheel and housing is completed, you can slide it easely to the pipe and attach it to the clmaps. Now, you can hang on your bikes and slide the in the corner.

I attached one with the front wheel up and one down in the change so all of our six bikes found place and after sliding together they took not more the 1.6m in the width.

They now hang on since 2 weeks and still there (15th oct. 17). If there is something to become a problem in stability, I will update this thing.

The hole for the M5 nut is a little bit thight, I used a screwdriver and a small hammer to get it in.

Takio (as I named him after a Japanese warrior) was fine at first in the large water column, but his fins have gotten so large that I see him lounging about on any surface he can find and swimming seems to be quite impractical and cumbersome with such large fins. So I decided to make him a platform where he can rest at a comfortable distance to the surface for air.

I used one of the suckers from my heating element to stick the hammock onto the inside of the fish tank, so I hope you can use it with a sucker of your own - maybe just modify it if need be.

The 3D object posted here has regular quadrilaterals (e.g. squares), and non-regular pentagons with vertical lines of symmetry. title: CR-10 High Clearance Fang Mod for 5015 Fans

description.text:
I really love the high clearance fang mod made by Tacblades.

I really didn't like the high pitched whine that my OEM blower fan made though and that's what lead me to remix this.

This is exactly the same as the original, only this accepts a standard 5015 blower fan instead of the OEM fan in the original.

For fitting instructions, see here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2544186

I'm currently using this fan: https://e3d-online.com/50x50x15mm-12v-dc-side-blow-fan

Note: There is a common 'HK Fan' available everywhere that does not like anything less than 12vdc. This is not good if you plan to run your fan at speeds lower than 100% as the HK Fan will stall if you try to run it at lower speeds.

I used a stainless M3x25 cap-head screw with an M3 nyloc nut and a couple of washers to fix the fan to the fang mod.

Be sure to check out my CR10 custom frame trims here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2639030

title: Zombie Pikachu coming out of my head

description.text:
As I'm performing as a zombie in Little Tokyo for the 2018 Thrill the World event, I wanted to go with an Anime theme. Hence, zombie Pikachu coming out of my head.

The Pikachu doll (fair use!) was from Amazon, as was the hat. I 3D printed the Pikachu skull (based on bfince's cat skull), and inserted it into the head, Terminator style. I also designed a "skull cap" with a hole and brains coming out.

Small plush Pikachu: https://smile.amazon.com/gp/product/B00GGKKXC8/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

Ash hat: https://smile.amazon.com/gp/product/B00A4XBTX0/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

I also used Great Stuff spray foam (windows and doors) to fill in some "brains."

For the STL files, I'm including the modified cat skull, 4 versions of the skull cap. One with no brains in case someone wants to use it. One low poly count brain version, one with a higher poly count (It may be 5mm shorter than the previous ones, after test fitting for my own head). The 4th one has the doll support I glued on pre-merged with the skull cap.

I'm holding a Pokeball designed by Intentional3D: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:411193 The little Squirtle inside is a friend's crochet creation.

Here's the Imgur album on the design: https://imgur.com/a/lFLDL

Basically, I took that skull cap, scaled it up, made a "hole version" offset a few mm down to make the whole thing thinner. Cut off the bottom with a box to give it a printable edge, and cut out the jagged hole with a bunch of polygons.

I imported that into Oculus Medium as a stamp, and sculpted some brains around the edges, exported that back into TinkerCAD to merge with the skull cap.

The cat skull was scaled upward and filled in with solid polygons to better fit the doll head.

Pained the "brains" a salmon color for a base coat. Will add some browns and reds. Some more detail on the skull cap. I really should have primed it first. Some painting done to darken the eye and nose socket, and make the tongue red. Dilute wash of red over a lot of the skull. Found I needed a support structure to hold up the doll. Printed this up, and glued it on. New version of the file has it incorporated Skull placed into doll.

This was designed for the #TealDroneChallenge and meant to not only offer more pro pilots with better options but to allow more types of pilots to enjoy this frame. Holes on the sides allow for antenna routing for people wanting to use extended antennas or UHF receivers for long range flights or just more solid connections. The camera plate sits with a 20 degree up tilt for the best angle for freestyle or even some racing for all to enjoy while not limiting camera use. The extended camera mount can easily hold a GoPro Session, Foxeer Box, Foxeer Legend 3 or any of the most popular hd cameras loved by today's fpv pilots. The SMA mount in the back allows for not only standard sma vtx's to be used but also others like the TBS Tramp or FuriousFPV Stealth Race vtx that have m3 holes to securely mount the SMA to the frame and super easy to remove and do maintenance if need be. The fpv camera mount has been designed to hold a Foxeer Micro v2 or Runcam Micro v2 snugly and securely while also allowing full range of tilt from 0 degrees all the way up to 60 or higher for those extreme pilots and also allowing for full ventilation to keep your electronics nice and cool while still being super sexy.

Holes have been added near the rear not only to vent out the heat generated inside the shell but also as mounting points if needed to run that newest vtx, new rx or anything else you may need like a Loc8tor in case you go down. Ensures your quad isn't lost and above all keeps it protected and looking neat

This is my newly designed and built Makerbot Replicator Enclosure that does not require a laser cutter to make.  It can be built using your Makerbot Replicator, a band saw, drill press, and one screw driver for assembly.  It uses 1/4 inch thick acrylic plastic for all the clear parts so that it will not sag because it is to light weight for the sizes that are needed.  It cost less than half of what it would be to have the parts laser cut for you. The top hood and front window opening are easily removed in seconds without tools so it is simple to access the Makerbot when you want to make adjustments, print a part or remove finished parts.

The first step in creating the enclosure is to cut out all of the clear acrylic plastic parts using a band saw and a drill press. The only part that is a little complicated to make is the front window. In the top center of the part is a 1/4 inch radius shown on the drawing for the part. To make this radius first drill a 1/2 inch hole and then mark the rest of the profile per the drawing provided. Do not remove any of the plastic film that is normally on acrylic plastic panels. This protects the part while you are cutting, drilling or sanding edges. It also makes it easier to mark the part as a Sharpie pen works best and the marks will not remain on the part once it is completed when the plastic film is removed just before final assembly.
The complete assembly is put together using a variety of brackets printed on the Makerbot and held together using 10-32 x 1 inch machine bolts and nuts. Forty-two bolts and nuts are required for the assembly. All Makerbot parts have recessed areas for the nuts so no wrench is needed to put the assembly together. Just a screw driver is all you will need. Refer to the parts illustration as to the correct location of each part. The corner mounts #1 and #2 are bolted together first for each corner. The recessed nuts will sit just below the surface of the assembly so it will mount easily onto to the Makerbot Replicator
Take your time with the cutting and drilling as all holes are 1/4 inch which will allow tolerance to be built into the design to allow for correct fit when assembly is underway. All hood panels should sit flush with the top inner surface of the Makerbot so that holes will line up for the bolts to be installed. If the bottom edge of a panel does not sit flush then recut the notches that are in the panels on both ends to clear the mated printed Makerbot corner pieces. This will allow for better alignment of mounting holes in the assembly.
After all acrylic parts have been cut, sand edges smooth using sand paper being careful not to scuff the facing surfaces. The side windows for the Makerbot Replicator are drilled and cut to make the slots for assembly into the Makerbot. To hold these parts in place you will need to print out "Side Panel Clips" by Etrohn found here on Thingiverse. These are quick and easy to print on the Makerbot and easy to install in the assembly. If you should need more information and photos of this build please check out my blog site for more help. Thetinkersworkshop.blogspot.com

title: Tabor pipes in G, Bb, C, and D

description.text:
This is a whistle with three finger holes that you can play with one hand, leaving the other hand free to bang a "tabor" drum.  
This is the classic medieval and renaissance one-man-band, essential for throwing a proper party throughout period. Shakespear's fool William Kemp once danced a jig for nine days and covered a hundred miles to the sound of pipe and tabor.  
By using the second, third and fourth registers of the pipe you can play a complete scale over about an octave and a half. The different registers are reached by blowing harder or softer. Madness! It becomes natural with a little practice. Now play the drum at the same time.

I've included four version, in keys of G, Bb, C and D (in order of decreasing size). Lengths of these instruments are listed below. Renaissance illustrations seem to be about the G size, or even larger. The G version is about the length of an alto recorder, but plays an octave higher -- these are quite high pitched instruments for their length. G - 432mm
Bb - 362mm
C - 321mm
D - 285mm Download and unzip your chosen zip file. The instrument is given as segments, which we will weld or glue together. Several possible segmentations are included in each zip file, choose a segmentation that you can print with your printer. When printing, the wall thickness and/or fill percentage should be quite high. A stiff wall is necessary for the instrument to sound loudly and without needing excessive air flow. If you can feel the wall vibrating as you play, that is energy being lost. After printing, ensure the tops of the pieces are flat. I like to tidy things up with a hobby knife. (Leave the prongs intact!) Having printed the pieces, they need to be connected together. ABS plastic: Dip the ends of pieces you wish to join in acetone for 15 seconds, then hold them firmly together. The model includes guide prongs that will ensure the correct orientation of the pieces. Use appropriate safety equipment when using acetone (gloves, goggles, good ventilation, etc)! Though not essential, I like to put the completed instrument in an acetone vapour chamber to smooth the surface. This produces a nicer finish and may improve the loudness. My acetone vapour chamber is simply a large glass vase. In this I put a small cup of acetone blown on with a small fan. I put in the instrument and seal the top with gladwrap, then leave everything for an hour and a half. Again, be careful around acetone! PLA plastic: I am told that the segments can be joined using epoxy glue. Make sure there are absolutely no holes in the joins, or the instrument won't sound.

See the file "three-hole-whistle-fingering.pdf" for the fingering system, which is quite simple. The trick is all in the breath control.  
See the file "music.pdf" for some renaissance dance tunes to get you started.

These instruments were designed using Demakein, version 0.16. You could use Demakein to create pipes in different keys. Demakein can also be used to design a variety of other woodwind instruments. If you know a little Python, you can also design novel woodwind instruments to your own specifications.

title: Anet A8 Backframe Stabilizer "I dun goofed"-Edition

description.text:
I had it with these monkeyfighting rods on these monday to friday flights. Or something like that.

But seriously though. The endcaps for the Y-axis rods that were delivered with the A8 are a huge mess. I get them to break off all the time, so now I thought it's time to rethink this.

And this is what has come out of said thoughtprocess. [Insert Victory Fanfare]
My printer is now easily the stable-est it has been in the whole 2 months I've been owning it. No more Y-axis ghosting, no more wobble, nothing.

It should also provide a decent amount of support for the original acrylic backframe of the A8.

This has been 'designed' with this Y-frame replacement in mind, since it was already installed in my printer: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2058789
So no worries about threaded rods that are too short or anything.

Instructions, just in case it's not already clear by the pictures:

  • Print this (Duh)
  • But at 101% scale (sliced in Cura 3.0), cause I dun goof'd.
  • Unscrew the two nuts from the threaded rod at the back of the printer
    ** also: Unscrew everything else between the two nuts.
  • Heat deez nuts up with a jet torch lighter, try to fit them into the hexagonal shapes on the bracket. They are meant to hold in place, so no worries about the nuts melting your precious PLA-Workpiece (i.e. it HAS TO happen.)
  • Put the backframe bracket where the nuts were. It should fit right in place.
  • Screw the threaded rods from the front into the nuts.
  • Replace the M3X18 screws with M3X30 screws and screw everything together*.

Boom, no more breaking little shits that'll cost you your nerves.

  • Please note: I have been building upon the acryl frame thing by SmallArtFly and it wouldn't quite fit in the end. If you're unsure whether it'll fit try the "honeycombed" Version, it makes it much easier to screw together, in case a hole or two are blocked. Also: A lighter and a small screwdriver, which you can push going from the acrylic side through the bracket should make your life much easier.

  • Please note 2: Since Fusion 360 wouldn't let me access the timeline-tool when creating this, I can't really change anything. So this thing stands "as is". It's complete. No updates, no fixes, niente, nothing, nada.

P.S.: Please excuse my super duper shitty camera. Kthxbai.

description.text: A set of 3d printable bike rollers I designed and made. Over 100 hours of printing and almost 2kg of plastic! Indoor training time! Check out the instructions for details. http://youtu.be/nO8m7p93CHg

All the parts were printed in PLA on my Makerbot Replicator 2. I printed the center roller sections with 4 shells and 20% infill. The roller ends are 3 shells 10%infill. The bearing supports are 3 shells 10% infill also. The roller ends needed supports turned on (for the belt groove). The bearing supports needed a tiny bit of heat to let the bearings seat. All hole sizes are adjusted for correct sizing once sliced with MakerWare. There are two center section options:
A: 3 piece centers, you will need 3 per roller (9 total).
B: single piece center, you will need 1 per roller ( 3 total).
Option A allows for stronger rollers and fewer print failures due to overly long prints. It also means a smaller piece to replace if you have a roller break. I used a bit of glue between roller sections on the driven rollers. After positioning the rollers on the side rails, measure your belt length with a fair bit of stretch. Fuse the ends together with heat (I used my soldering iron set to about 450ÃÂ F). Trim the flashing then reinstall the belt There are extra belt grooves in the rollers if you want to drive a resistance unit or other things. 36 x M3 x 10mm SHCS (mcmaster 91292A113) 6 x R8 bearings (mcmaster 60355K601) 3 x 1/2" x 16" Shafts (mcmaster 6061K432) 12 x Set screw shaft collars (mcmaster 9414T11) aprox 8ft 3/16" urethane round belt (mcmaser 59725K703) 2 x 5' lengths 1/2" EMT conduit (sourced from Home Depot)
